tection and resolution workflows.\n\n### 4. Potential Future Considerations  \n- **Performance**: Git operations may become slower with large datasets or frequent commits\u2014consider shallow clones, sparse checkouts, or periodic compaction.  \n- **Conflict Handling**: May need custom merge drivers or UI for resolving complex data conflicts (beyond text files).  \n- **Security**: Ensure sensitive data in git history is protected (e.g., via encryption or `.gitignore` patterns).  \n- **Backup and Recovery**: Leverage git\u2019s redundancy for disaster recovery, but monitor repository integrity.  \n- **Tooling**: Could extend with hooks (e.g., pre-commit validation) or integrations with CI/CD for automated checks on stored data.  \n\nThis decision aligns with a **\"git-native\" philosophy**, using version control not just for code but as a collaborative data backbone. It promotes transparency, auditability, and team synergy, though it introduces a learning curve for non-git-savvy users.",
